@database "ReadThisFirst!"


@node Main "Important stuff that you should know..."
                               @{b}Trip In A Vein@{ub}

                             An @{i}AGA@{ui} animation by

                              @{u}Jonathan McBrien@{uu}
                                     of
                        @{b}D I G I T A L    R E T I N A@{ub}

            @{"Firstly...                                       " link Firstly}
            @{"Installing to harddisk                           " link InstallHD}
            @{"Viewing the animation after harddisk installation" link AfterInstalling}
            @{"Installing to RAM                                " link InstallRAM}
            @{"Deleting the animation from harddisk             " link Remove}
            @{"Other stuff                                      " link Other}
            @{"And finally...                                   " link Finally}
@endnode

@node Firstly "Firstly..."
Hi! And thanks for being interested in this animation.

I guess  that you're thinking  something like "Aw no! Not @{i}another@{ui} damn readme
file. I just wanna see the animation!"

Just take your time and read this AmigaGuide document. It might just save you
a load of unnecessary hassle later on!

What I will tell you at this  stage is that to be able  to get anywhere  with
this  animation  you  will  need  at  least @{b}5 meg of RAM.@{ub}  A  harddisk  isn't
absolutely  necessary,  but i f you have  both the memory  and the  harddisk,
you're flying. By the way, you haven't got a mission of  seeing this thing if
you don't at least have the memory.

@{b}BBS Users!!@{ub} Although  the contents  of this set of  animation disks
may @{i}not@{ui} be altered in any way whatsoever, you have my permission to
archive this set of seven disks for  oploading onto bulletin boards.
@endnode

@node InstallHD "Installing to harddisk"
To install the animation to harddisk, simply double click on the InstallToHD1
icon on this disk. Your  machine will then load  in each of the parts  of the
animation  and install  them  to your  harddisk  as one file, as  well as the
other associated files for this animation.

@{b}Nothing@{ub} will be copied to your harddisk that is not needed!

              @{"What to do if your work partition is called DH1:" link DH1}
@endnode

@node DH1 "What to do if your work partition is called DH1:, and not HD1:"
If this is the case on your  system, simply double click on the icon labelled
"InstallToDH1".  This will  install the  animation to  the work  partition of
your harddisk.

However, there is one more task for you to perform...

Find the file in the S directory of disk one called "PlayFromHD".

Replace any occurrence of HD1: with DH1:

@{b}THAT'S IT!!@{ub}

If you do have to make an alteration  to this file, please remember to change
it back to the way  you got it before sending a copy of this  animation on to
someone else! You may cause them a lot of unnecessary confusion otherwise.

I guess I should offer you an apology  for this sort of hotch-potch method of
harddisk  installation, but it was  the best compromise that I could  come up
with. Besides I don't think that it really is that much bother.
@endnode

@node AfterInstalling "Viewing the animation."
Providing  that the  install script  worked OK for  you, and it  sure as hell
should have, you are will now be ready to view the animation.

All you'll need to do is reboot  with @{b}disk one.@{ub} You will also need to do this
every time you want to view the complete animation.
@endnode

@node Remove "Deleting the animation from your harddisk"
When you decide that you no  longer want the animation  on your harddisk, run
the  appropriate UninstallFromHD  script to  delete all the associated  files
from your HD.

Like the install scripts, there  is one for those of you whose  harddisks are
called @{b}HD1:@{ub} and for those whose harddisks are called @{b}DH1:@{ub}

         @{">Click here if you don't trust scripts that delete things<" link NoTrust}
@endnode

@node NoTrust "Deleting the animation files manually."
Only the files  associated with "Trip In A Vein" will be deleted from your HD
by  the  delete  from HD scripts, so you  can rest  assured that there  isn't
anything  malicious  in there. All the same, if you want  total piece of mind
and want to delete everything yourself by  hand the files you should look for
on the root directory of your harddisk are:

Club1200Logo.IFF
DigitalRetinaLogo.IFF
Intro.EXE
Outro.EXE
KillAGA
TripInAVein.ANIM
ViewTek
@endnode


@node InstallRAM "Installing to RAM"
Don't worry, my lovelies! You  can get to see the  animation too! Provided of
that you  have  at least  @{b}5 meg@{ub}  of  RAM  in your  machine, though this  will
probably mean that you'll have 6 meg of RAM.

Just double  click on  the "InstallToRAM" icon on this disk. Everything  that
is needed will be installed to RAM and played directly from there.

The downside is  that you'll have  to re-install the whole thing if you  ever
want to watch the animation at a later date, and it takes quite a while!
@endnode

@node Other "Other stuff"
This is  my first raytraced  animation  to  be  released into public  domain,
though it  isn't my  @{i}first@{ui} raytraced  animation! See the outro at the  end of
the animation for more details.

The outro will also  present to you, some information about the animation and
@{b}D I G I T A L   R E T I N A.@{ub}
@endnode

@node Finally "And finally..."
Thanks for being  patient enough to  read through  this  AmigaGuide. I  think
you'll appreciate it when it comes to installing to animation.

Hopefully this won't be the last animation I'll  release onto the PD circuit.
At the moment I'm working hard  on my next one, which I hope will be finished
be the end of September, right on time for me going to uni!

@{"Hellos and thanks to..." link Hellos}

I'll have another yap at ya in my next animation, 'til then, bye bye!

Jonathan McBrien. Friday, 12th August 1994
@endnode

@node Hellos
Big hellos to  Mark Wylie (Silent  Warrior/PCA), Dave  Bruntnell (Mr B./PCA),
Andy  MacDonald (Orion/PCA),  Mike at  Club 1200,  Mercenary,  Neon,  Silver,
Scarface,  Fat  Will, Grieg  Harper at  Alpha PD  and anyone  who  I may have
forgotten or know me and happen to be reading this.

We all have our little gripes  about @{b}Imagine 3@{ub} (like incompatibility with old
version project  files, memory  wastage, slice  function  still  not  working
properly, lack of  fullscreen crosshair for Set Zone, etc.) but  why the hell
didn't @{b}Impulse@{ub} include some PostScript fonts with the program for  the Spline
Editor? It's  great to have the  beginnings of a Spline  Editor, but the lack
of tools in the current version of @{b}Imagine@{ub}  means that this editor  is really
only of use for manipulating font objects. C'mon guys, use  your commonsense!
So a  double  helping of  thanks goes  to me good  mate  @{b}Mark Wylie@{ub}  for  the
plethora of  PS fonts  he sent to me straight off his  CD ROM collection when
all others failed!!! Cheers Mark!

Big thanks  to the folks at @{b}17Bit Software@{ub} for  keeping @{i}Tympanic  Membrane@{ui} in
their adverts for so long. Cheers guys, may your harddisks never crash!

And a  massive  hello  to the people at @{b}Amiga  Format@{ub}, who  for the past  ten
months have refused to print any of my letters, even  though they were, in my
opinion some of the best pieces of prose  that could have graced their pages.
Ah well, some  other time maybe! Keep up the good work there people  and keep
yourselves the best Amiga mag on the shelves!

And lastly, but by no means whatsoever leastly, a @{b}HUGE@{ub} thanks to me good mate
@{b}Terry@{ub} @{i}"Riches To Rags"@{ui} @{b}Beatty@{ub}  for coding  the wee intro  and outro  to  this
animation. All I did was tell the guy what I  wanted and he had the things up
and running an hour and a half later.

Cheers Tel! This thing wouldn't have  been as well presented if it wasn't for
you!

@{"This has always bugged me, does anyone know the answer?" link Hole}
@endnode

@node Hole "Arrrghhh!!! What the hell would happen?!??!!"
Right, hands up any of you who have lay awake in your beds at night thinking
one of those silly, niggly little things that refuses to let you go to sleep
until you've got the answer?

Well, here's one that's been bugging me for ages and as I didn't keep
physics up at school I can't be sure what would happen.

And here I am typing this, and passing the problem onto you poor people.

Suppose you dug a hole straight through the Earth, right to the other side.
Suppose also that you jumped into said hole. What the hell would happen?!

Would you build up so much momentum on the way through that you would shoot
out the other side and into space?

Or would you fall down, until you got halfway through at which point you
would be `falling' up (think about it), and then fall down again and so on
until you eventually came to rest at the dead centre of the Earth, whereupon
you could do crazy somersaults, have 360 degree raves, or do really cool
bicycle kicks without having to worry about which way you were going to land?

Or would this happen, but you would get squashed into bits due to the force
of gravity in every direction?

If anyone is educated enough in physics out there to competently answer this
one, please drop me a line at the address given in the outro! Even if you
have more theories as to what might happen I'd like to hear from you!

You got more than you bargained for when you got this animation, eh?
@endnode


